properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Locations: southern New Brunswick. Time span: early Sunday morning until early Sunday evening. Remarks: showers or periods of rain will continue tonight then change to freezing rain early Sunday morning and then change over or mix with ice pellets for more central areas Sunday afternoon as temperatures fall rapidly during the day. properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain and warm temperatures for tonight followed by freezing rain, rain and ice pellets on Sunday. Total rainfall: 10-30 mm tonight and Sunday morning. Freezing rain: significant ice accretion likely overnight tonight into Sunday, with the most accretion expected over parts of the Annapolis Valley and central and eastern areas of mainland Nova Scotia. Freezing rain ending Sunday evening. Winds: gusts to 70-80 km/h in the Tantramar Marsh region this evening. Gusts of 40 km/h on Sunday over northern areas. Locations: Nova Scotia, excluding southwesternmost regions and northern Cape Breton. Remarks: rain and very mild temperatures associated with brisk southwest winds can be expected this evening. Temperatures will fall rapidly overnight tonight over northern areas of the province and over most other areas of the province early on Sunday morning. Rain will change to freezing rain or ice pellets over much of the province by early Sunday morning. These conditions are expected to persist throughout the day Sunday, although some areas along the Atlantic coast will change to rain as temperatures rise somewhat on Sunday afternoon. Significant impacts from these changing precipitation types are likely. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Utility outages may occur. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rainfall, combined with melting snow, is expected. The frozen ground has a reduced ability to absorb this rainfall. Rain changing to freezing rain and ice pellets tonight. A moisture laden low from Texas will continue to spread rain across Eastern Ontario early this evening, with most areas receiving a total of 20 to 30 mm of rain. The rain is then expected to change over to freezing rain mixed with ice pellets by mid evening as temperatures slide down to the zero degree mark. Since the ground is frozen, the winter rainfall warning criterion of 25 mm in 24 hours is being met. For information concerning flooding, please consult your local conservation authority or Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources and Forestry district office. Freezing rain may last for several hours tonight before becoming mixed with ice pellets or a couple cm of snow Sunday. Significant ice accretion of 10 to 20 mm is possible tonight from the freezing rain. A Freezing rain warning is also in effect. Brisk northerly winds Sunday are also possible. These winds coupled with ice build up on tree branches and power lines could cause a few power outages. Travel will be impacted throughout Southern Ontario Saturday into Sunday. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain is expected or occurring. Light and intermittent freezing drizzle, ice pellets and snow over the Bruce Peninsula will become continuous again this evening. As a moisture laden Texas Low passes by to the south tonight, freezing rain mixed with ice pellets is expected to return to only the southern parts of the region near Wiarton and Sauble Beach. Ice accretion of 2 to 5 millimetres is possible tonight over southern parts of the Bruce Peninsula. Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 20 to 25 cm is expected. Snow at times heavy will affect these regions on Sunday. Total amounts of 15 to 25 centimetres are expected. ### Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.
